The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business
 Tuesday, June 01, 2004  Business Briefs																								 New Delhi, May 31: International rating agency Standard amp; Poors today said Indias rating can improve if the new government reduces fiscal deficit and continues reforms to maintain a high economic growth. S amp;P, which pegged Indias GDP growth at 6 per cent for this year compared with 8 per cent last year, also said the budget for 2004-05 will be a litmus test for the Congress-led United Progressive Alliance government. A better fiscal performance, along with structural reforms to maintain the countrys growth prospects and its strong external profile could lead to an improved foreign currency rating, S amp;P director Ping Chew said in a statement.																								 Mumbai, May 31: Sterlite Industries Ltd has revised the terms and conditions of its proposed rights issue. The board has decided to offer shares at Rs 550 apiece in the ratio of 1:2.																								 New Delhi, May 31: The group of 20 developing countries, spearheaded by India and Brazil, have come out with a proposal in a bid to break the deadlock in WTO negotiations. It emphasises on differentiated tariff cuts for developing countries.																								 Mumbai, May 31: Union civil aviation minister Praful Patel said today the government is taking a relook at the aircraft acquisition proposals of Air-India and Indian Airlines.																								 Mumbai, May 31: The Centre today reappointed M. Damodaran as chairman and managing director of the Industrial Development Bank of India up to May 31, 2007.
